Scholarship Opportunities Available to D211 High School Seniors, Grads http://www.excelbeyond211.dollarsforscholars.org/index.php?section=chapterWebsite&action=main&fwID=2259
Excel Beyond 211 Dollars for Scholars® (EB211) is dedicated to mentoring and providing financial information and opportunities to select students who are graduating or have graduated from Palatine, William Fremd, James B. Conant, Schaumburg, and Hoffman Estates High Schools in District 211. EB211 invests in college-ready, first-generation students from low-income families, aiming to increase their college successes and completion rates. EB211 helps these students achieve their educational goals by providing a one-to-one adult mentor to assist each EB211 scholar. For more information or to browse scholarship opportunities, visit the EB211 website. Village of Schaumburg, Illinois Government

post_text:
Village of Schaumburg, Illinois Government
Schaumburg High School graduate Matthew Williams is one of just 300 high school students nationwide – and one of just 5 in the Chicago area – to be recognized as a 2020 Bank of America Student Leader. The program, now in its 16th year, provides students a summer of paid, virtual leadership experience, civic engagement, and workforce skills-building. As a Student Leader, he will participate in a collaborative, mentoring-focused project to educate community residents on the importance of voting and engage in conversations around democracy, social justice, civil rights, and how to build a more diverse and inclusive society. Matthew is a former recipient of the Schaumburg Volunteer of the Year award in the youth category. Congratulations, Matthew!
text:
Village of Schaumburg, Illinois Government
Schaumburg High School graduate Matthew Williams is one of just 300 high school students nationwide – and one of just 5 in the Chicago area – to be recognized as a 2020 Bank of America Student Leader. The program, now in its 16th year, provides students a summer of paid, virtual leadership experience, civic engagement, and workforce skills-building. As a Student Leader, he will participate in a collaborative, mentoring-focused project to educate community residents on the importance of voting and engage in conversations around democracy, social justice, civil rights, and how to build a more diverse and inclusive society. Matthew is a former recipient of the Schaumburg Volunteer of the Year award in the youth category. Congratulations, Matthew!

post_text: Our friends at Schaumburg Township District Library are looking for your support in marking the 50th anniversary of Earth Day. See below on how to support this initiative.
shared_text:
Schaumburg Township District Library
April 15 at 9:19 PM ·

Next Wednesday marks the 50th anniversary of Earth Day. Help us celebrate by creating an original piece of art around the theme Take Action: Earth Matters. Share a photo of your art on social media and tag us or email it to marketing@stdl.org. Then, on Earth Day, we'll share a gallery of all your fantastic art celebrating our planet.

post_text: Take a look at this interview with Schaumburg High School alumn Michael Roark
shared_text:
DAILYHERALD.COM
Actor and Schaumburg native Michael Roark still a 'classic' suburban guy

Daily Herald shared a link to the group: Everything Schaumburg.
September 4, 2019 at 5:06 PM ·

"I think growing up in Schaumburg and Chicagoland instilled in me a willingness to work," said Michael Roark, a Schaumburg High School grad. "I have been to most of the rest of the country and while there is great work ethic all over, there are also many places where people just don't work nearly as hard as where I grew up."

Township High School District 211

Village of Schaumburg, Illinois Government
August 27, 2019 at 4:35 PM ·

Have you used the village’s website to learn more about a topic, find information on a service, or obtain details about an event? If so, we want to hear from you!

The Village of Schaumburg invites the public to submit a brief survey that includes input and feedback about the village’s website, www.schaumburg.com, so that information can be collected regarding user habits, likes and dislikes. Surveys are anonymous, and data will be reviewed by the village to determine how the site could be improved in the future to offer a better experience for users.

Survey responses, which should take about 5-7 minutes to complete, will be collected until the end of business day on Friday, Sept. 6. The village thanks you for your participation.

Take the survey now:
www.surveymonkey.com/r/YY7BK3M
